body:
When member function of base class is called inside `super.new()` argument list, simulation is terminated due to `SEGFAULT`. Even though `LRM` fobids such cases they are pretty common in `SystemVerilog` examples - expecially inside `UVM Cookbook` (`c_stimulus`, `Uvm_register_spi_bl`, `Uvm_tb_build_bl_tb`, `Uvm_tb_build_ss_tb`).

Example from `Uvm_tb_build_ss_tb`:
```systemverilog
function new(string name = "gpio_ctrl_reg");
  super.new(name, 32, build_coverage(UVM_CVR_FIELD_VALS));
  add_coverage(build_coverage(UVM_CVR_FIELD_VALS));
  if(has_coverage(UVM_CVR_FIELD_VALS))
    cg_vals = new();
endfunction
```

Stand alone example:

```systemverilog
class foo;
  function new(int x);
  endfunction

  protected function int get_x();
    foo f = this;
    return 0;
  endfunction
endclass

class bar extends foo;
  function new();
    super.new(get_x());
  endfunction
endclass

module top;
  initial begin
    bar b = new();
  end
endmodule 
```

Above snippet compiles but when run it is terminated due to a segmentation fault.

## Why it happens?

This happens because we're constructing (and destructing) a reference (`VlClassRef`) to `this` in `get_x()`.

This obviously increments/decrements the reference counter. In Verilator, reference counters are stored within objects (they're intrusive shared pointers).

This is to facilitate construction of such pointers just using `VlClassRef{this}`. This is needed for coroutines – if a coroutine metod is suspended, it needs `this` alive, even if nothing else points at it.

`SEGFAULT` is raised because `get_x()` is called before any constructor inside a lambda:
```c++
Vx___024unit__03a__03abar::Vx___024unit__03a__03abar(Vx__Syms* __restrict vlSymsp)
    : Vx___024unit__03a__03afoo(vlSymsp, ([&]() {
            IData/*31:0*/ __Vfunc_get_x__1__Vfuncout;
            __Vfunc_get_x__1__Vfuncout = 0;
            this->__VnoInFunc_get_x(vlSymsp, __Vfunc_get_x__1__Vfuncout);
            return (__Vfunc_get_x__1__Vfuncout);
        }())) {
    VL_DEBUG_IF(VL_DBG_MSGF("+          Vx___024unit__03a__03abar::new\n"); );
    // Body
    _ctor_var_reset(vlSymsp);
    ;
}
```

## Solution

The simplest possible solution would be to just introduce `init()` functions. Generated `C++` would look like this:

```c++
#include <iostream>

struct VlSymsp {};

class Base {
protected:
    void init(VlSymsp vlSymsp, int o) { 
        std::cout << "[DEBUG]: GOT: " << o << '\n';
    }
public:
    Base() { }
    Base(VlSymsp vlSymsp, int constructorArgument) {
        init(vlSymsp, constructorArgument);
    }
};

class Derived : Base {
protected:
    void init(VlSymsp vlSymsp) {
        Base::init(vlSymsp, 3);
        // Further construction e.g. user defined part
    }
public:
    Derived() { }
    Derived(VlSymsp vlSymsp) { init(vlSymsp); }
};
```

This solution has:

 - RAII
 - constructor arguments

Also, there are no heavy objects in use inside generated `C++` in user classes (that I am aware of) which initialization can't be postponed without hurting performance.

Worth noticing is also the fact that by `init()` function I don't mean some function that it is user (creator of the object) responsibility to call it but rather something that is some kind of implementation detail of a constructor.

